# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mitre-capec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] In computer science, **attack patterns** are a group of rigorous methods for finding bugs or errors in code related to computer security.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Attack patterns are often used for testing purposes and are very important for ensuring that potential vulnerabilities are prevented.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] The attack patterns themselves can be used to highlight areas which need to be considered for security hardening in a software application.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] They also provide, either physically or in reference, the common solution pattern for preventing the attack.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Such a practice can be termed *defensive coding patterns*.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Attack patterns define a series of repeatable steps that can be applied to simulate an attack against the security of a system.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] There are several ways to categorize attack patterns.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Another way is to group them into general categories.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Attack Patterns are structured very much like structure of Design patterns.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Using this format is helpful for standardizing the development of attack patterns and ensures that certain information about each pattern is always documented the same way.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] The label given to the pattern which is commonly used to refer to the pattern in question.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] The pattern type and its associated subtypes aid in classification of the pattern.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This allows users to rapidly locate and identify pattern groups that they will have to deal with in their security efforts.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Each pattern will have a type, and zero or more subtypes that identify the category of the attack pattern.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Typical types include Injection Attack, Denial of Service Attack, Cryptanalysis Attack, etc.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Examples of typical subtypes for Denial Of Service, for example, would be: DOS – Resource Starvation, DOS-System Crash, DOS-Policy Abuse.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Another important use of this field is to ensure that true patterns are not repeated unnecessarily.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Often it is easy to confuse a new exploit with a new attack.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] New exploits are created all the time for the same attack patterns.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] The Buffer Overflow Attack Pattern is a good example.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] There are many known exploits and viruses that take advantage of a Buffer Overflow vulnerability.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Therefore, the Type and Subtype classification mechanism provides a way to classify a pattern.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] If the pattern you are creating doesn't have a unique Type and Subtype, chances are it is a new exploit for an existing pattern.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This section is also used to indicate if it is possible to automate the attack.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] If it is possible to automate the attack, it is recommended to provide a sample in the Sample Attack Code section which is described below.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Certain attacks may be known by several different names.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This field is used to list those other names.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This is a description of the attack itself, and where it may have originated from.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] It is essentially a free-form field that can be used to record information that doesn’t easily fit into the other fields.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This field identifies the intended result of the attacker.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This indicates the attacker’s main target and goal for the attack itself.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] For example, The Attacker Intent of a DOS – Bandwidth Starvation attack is to make the target web site unreachable to legitimate traffic.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This field records the attacker’s reason for attempting this attack.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] It may be to crash a system in order to cause financial harm to the organization, or it may be to execute the theft of critical data in order to create financial gain for the attacker.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This field is slightly different from the Attacker Intent field in that it describes why the attacker may want to achieve the Intent listed in the Attacker Intent field, rather than the physical result of the attack.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This field indicates the specific type of vulnerability that creates the attack opportunity in the first place.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] An example of this in an Integer Overflow attack would be that the integer-based input field is not checking size of the value of the incoming data to ensure that the target variable is capable of managing the incoming value.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This is the vulnerability that the associated exploit will take advantage of in order to carry out the attack.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] The Participants are one or more entities that are required for this attack to succeed.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This includes the victim systems as well as the attacker and the attacker’s tools or system components.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] The name of the entity should be accompanied by a brief description of their role in the attack and how they interact with each other.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] These are one or more diagrams of the attack to visually explain how the attack is executed.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This diagram can take whatever form is appropriate but it is recommended that the diagram be similar to a system or class diagram showing data flows and the components involved.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Every attack must have some context to operate in and the conditions that make the attack possible.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This section describes what conditions are required and what other systems or situations need to be in place in order for the attack to succeed.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] For example, for the attacker to be able to execute an Integer Overflow attack, they must have access to the vulnerable application.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] That will be common amongst most of the attacks.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] However, if the vulnerability only exposes itself when the target is running on a remote RPC server, that would also be a condition that would be noted here.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] If it is possible to demonstrate the exploit code, this section provides a location to store the demonstration code.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] In some cases, such as a Denial of Service attack, specific code may not be possible.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] However, in Overflow, and Cross Site Scripting type attacks, sample code would be very useful.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Automated exploits are often found as viruses, worms and hacking tools.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] If there are any existing exploits known for the attack this section should be used to list a reference to those exploits.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] These references can be internal such as corporate knowledge bases, or external such as the various CERT, and Virus databases.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Exploits are not to be confused with vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] An Exploit is an automated or manual attack that utilises the vulnerability.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] It is not a listing of a vulnerability found in a particular product for example.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Follow-on attacks are any other attacks that may be enabled by this particular attack pattern.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] For example, a Buffer Overflow attack pattern, is usually followed by Escalation of Privilege attacks, Subversion attacks or setting up for Trojan Horse /Backdoor attacks.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This field can be particularly useful when researching an attack and identifying what other potential attacks may have been carried out or set up.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] The mitigation types are the basic types of mitigation strategies that would be used to prevent the attack pattern.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This would commonly refer to Security Patterns and Defensive Coding Patterns.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Mitigation Types can also be used as a means of classifying various attack patterns.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] By classifying Attack Patterns in this manner, libraries can be developed to implement particular mitigation types which can then be used to mitigate entire classes of Attack Patterns.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] These libraries can then be used and reused throughout various applications to ensure consistent and reliable coverage against particular types of attacks.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Since this is an attack pattern, the recommended mitigation for the attack can be listed here in brief.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] Ideally, this will point the user to a more thorough mitigation pattern for this class of attack.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This section will have a few subsections such as Related Patterns, Mitigation Patterns, Security Patterns, and Architectural Patterns.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] These are references to patterns that can support, relate to or mitigate the attack and the listing for the related pattern should note that.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] This section lists all the references to related alerts listings and publications such as listings in the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures list, CERT, SANS, and any related vendor alerts.
[src:mitre-capec/attack-pattern] These listings should be hyperlinked to the online alerts and listings in order to ensure it references the most up to date information possible.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] The **Common Weakness Enumeration** (**CWE**) is a category system for hardware and software weaknesses and vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] It is sustained by a community project with the goals of understanding flaws in software and hardware and creating automated tools that can be used to identify, fix, and prevent those flaws.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] The project is sponsored by the office of the U.S.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), which is operated by The MITRE Corporation, with support from US-CERT and the National Cyber Security Division of the U.S.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] The first release of the list and associated classification taxonomy was in 2006.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] Version 4.15 of the CWE standard was released in July 2024.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] CWE has over 600 categories, including classes for buffer overflows, path/directory tree traversal errors, race conditions, cross-site scripting, hard-coded passwords, and insecure random numbers.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) Compatibility program allows a service or a product to be reviewed and registered as officially "CWE-Compatible" and "CWE-Effective".
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] The program assists organizations in selecting the right software tools and learning about possible weaknesses and their possible impact.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] There are 56 organizations as of September 2019 that develop and maintain products and services that achieved CWE Compatible status.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] Some researchers think that ambiguities in CWE can be avoided or reduced.
[src:mitre-capec/common-weakness-enumeration] As of 4/16/2024, the CWE Compatibility Program has been discontinued.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] In computer security, a **vulnerability** is a flaw or weakness in a system's design, implementation, or management that can be exploited by a malicious actor to compromise its security.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts to achieve complete correctness, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs where the system does not behave as expected.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] If the bug could enable an attacker to compromise the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of system resources, it can be considered a vulnerability.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Insecure software development practices as well as design factors such as complexity can increase the burden of vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management includes identifying systems and prioritizing which are most important, scanning for vulnerabilities, and taking action to secure the system.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management typically is a combination of remediation, mitigation, and acceptance.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can be scored for severity according to the Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) and added to vulnerability databases such as the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) database.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] As of April 2026, more than 327,000 vulnerabilities had been recorded in the CVE database.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] A vulnerability is initiated when it is introduced into hardware or software.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] It becomes active and exploitable when the software or hardware containing the vulnerability is running.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability may be discovered by the administrator, vendor, or a third party.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Publicly disclosing the vulnerability (through a patch or otherwise) is associated with an increased risk of compromise, as attackers can use this knowledge to target existing systems before patches are implemented.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities will eventually end when the system is either patched or removed from use.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Software patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but zero-days are still liable for exploitation.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors, and the actual risk is dependent on the nature of the vulnerability as well as the value of the surrounding system.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Although some vulnerabilities can only be used for denial-of-service attacks, more dangerous ones allow the attacker to perform code injection without the user's awareness.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Only a minority of vulnerabilities allow for privilege escalation, which is typically necessary for more severe attacks.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Without a vulnerability, an exploit typically cannot gain access.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] It is also possible for malware to be installed directly, without an exploit, through social engineering or poor physical security such as an unlocked door or exposed port.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Poor software development practices can affect the likelihood of introducing vulnerabilities to a code base.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Lack of knowledge or training regarding secure software development, excessive pressure to deliver, or an excessively complex code base can all allow vulnerabilities to be introduced and left unnoticed.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] These factors can also be exacerbated if security is not prioritized by the company culture.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Inadequate code reviews can also lead to missed bugs, but there are also static code analysis tools that can be used during the code review process to help find some vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] DevOps, a development workflow that emphasizes automated testing and deployment to speed up the deployment of new features, often requires that many developers be granted access to change configurations, which can lead to deliberate or inadvertent inclusion of vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Compartmentalizing dependencies, which is often part of DevOps workflows, can reduce the attack surface by paring down dependencies to only what is necessary.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] If software as a service is used, rather than the organization's own hardware and software, the organization is dependent on the cloud services provider to prevent vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Access control vulnerabilities enable an attacker to access a system that is supposed to be restricted to them, or engage in privilege escalation.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] When the system fails to handle and exceptional or unanticipated condition correctly, an attacker can exploit the situation to gain access.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Configuration vulnerability come into existence when configuration settings cause risks to the system security, leading to such faults as unpatched software or file system permissions that do not sufficiently restrict access.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] A race condition—when timing or other external factors change the outcome and lead to inconsistent or unpredictable results—can cause a vulnerability.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Deliberate security bugs can be introduced during or after manufacturing and cause the integrated circuit not to behave as expected under certain specific circumstances.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Testing for security bugs in hardware is quite difficult due to limited time and the complexity of twenty-first century chips, while the globalization of design and manufacturing has increased the opportunity for these bugs to be introduced by malicious actors.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Although operating system vulnerabilities vary depending on the operating system in use, a common problem is privilege escalation bugs that enable the attacker to gain more access than they should be allowed.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Open-source operating systems such as Linux and Android have a freely accessible source code and allow anyone to contribute, which could enable the introduction of vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] However, the same vulnerabilities also occur in proprietary operating systems such as Microsoft Windows and Apple operating systems.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] All reputable vendors of operating systems provide patches regularly.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Client–server applications are downloaded onto the end user's computers and are typically updated less frequently than web applications.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Unlike web applications, they interact directly with a user's operating system.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Because they are inherently less secure than other applications, they are a leading source of data breaches and other security incidents.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] There is little evidence about the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of different cyberattack prevention measures.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Although estimating the risk of an attack is not straightforward, the mean time to breach and expected cost can be considered to determine the priority for remediating or mitigating an identified vulnerability and whether it is cost effective to do so.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of attack, achieving perfect security for a complex system is impossible, and many security measures have unacceptable cost or usability downsides.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] For example, reducing the complexity and functionality of the system is effective at reducing the attack surface.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Successful vulnerability management usually involves a combination of remediation (closing a vulnerability), mitigation (increasing the difficulty, and reducing the consequences, of exploits), and accepting some residual risk.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Often a defense in depth strategy is used for multiple barriers to attack.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Some organizations scan for only the highest-risk vulnerabilities as this enables prioritization in the context of lacking the resources to fix every vulnerability.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Increasing expenses is likely to have diminishing returns.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Remediation fixes vulnerabilities, for example by downloading a software patch.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability scanners are typically unable to detect zero-day vulnerabilities, but are more effective at finding known vulnerabilities based on a database.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] These systems can find some known vulnerabilities and advise fixes, such as a patch.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] However, they have limitations including false positives.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can only be exploited when they are active-the software in which they are embedded is actively running on the system.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Before the code containing the vulnerability is configured to run on the system, it is considered a carrier.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Dormant vulnerabilities can run, but are not currently running.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Software containing dormant and carrier vulnerabilities can sometimes be uninstalled or disabled, removing the risk.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Active vulnerabilities, if distinguished from the other types, can be prioritized for patching.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability mitigation is measures that do not close the vulnerability, but make it more difficult to exploit or reduce the consequences of an attack.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Reducing the attack surface, particularly for parts of the system with root (administrator) access, and closing off opportunities for exploits to engage in privilege exploitation is a common strategy for reducing the harm that a cyberattack can cause.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] If a patch for third-party software is unavailable, it may be possible to temporarily disable the software.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] A penetration test attempts to enter the system via an exploit to see if the system is insecure.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] If a penetration test fails, it does not necessarily mean that the system is secure.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Some penetration tests can be conducted with automated software that tests against existing exploits for known vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Other penetration tests are conducted by trained hackers.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Many companies prefer to contract out this work as it simulates an outsider attack.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability lifecycle begins when vulnerabilities are introduced into hardware or software.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Detection of vulnerabilities can be by the software vendor, or by a third party.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] In the latter case, it is considered most ethical to immediately disclose the vulnerability to the vendor so it can be fixed.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Government or intelligence agencies buy vulnerabilities that have not been publicly disclosed and may use them in an attack, stockpile them, or notify the vendor.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] As of 2013, the Five Eyes (United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand) captured the plurality of the market and other significant purchasers included Russia, India, Brazil, Malaysia, Singapore, North Korea, and Iran.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Organized criminal groups also buy vulnerabilities, although they typically prefer exploit kits.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Even vulnerabilities that are publicly known or patched are often exploitable for an extended period.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Security patches can take months to develop, or may never be developed.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] A patch can have negative effects on the functionality of software and users may need to test the patch to confirm functionality and compatibility.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Larger organizations may fail to identify and patch all dependencies, while smaller enterprises and personal users may not install patches.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Research suggests that risk of cyberattack increases if the vulnerability is made publicly known or a patch is released.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Cybercriminals can reverse engineer the patch to find the underlying vulnerability and develop exploits, often faster than users install the patch.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities become deprecated when the software or vulnerable versions fall out of use.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] This can take an extended period of time; in particular, industrial software may not be feasible to replace even if the manufacturer stops supporting it.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] A commonly used scale for assessing the severity of vulnerabilities is the open-source specification Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS).
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] CVSS evaluates the possibility to exploit the vulnerability and compromise data confidentiality, availability, and integrity.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] It also considers how the vulnerability could be used and how complex an exploit would need to be.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] The amount of access needed for exploitation and whether it could take place without user interaction are also factored in to the overall score.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Someone who discovers a vulnerability may disclose it immediately (full disclosure) or wait until a patch has been developed (responsible disclosure, or coordinated disclosure).
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] The former approach is praised for its transparency, but the drawback is that the risk of attack is likely to be increased after disclosure with no patch available.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Some vendors pay bug bounties to those who report vulnerabilities to them.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Not all companies respond positively to disclosures, as they can cause legal liability and operational overhead.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] There is no law requiring disclosure of vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] If a vulnerability is discovered by a third party that does not disclose to the vendor or the public, it is called a zero-day vulnerability, often considered the most dangerous type because fewer defenses exist.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] The most commonly used vulnerability dataset is Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE), maintained by Mitre Corporation.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] This information is shared into other databases, including the United States' National Vulnerability Database, where each vulnerability is given a risk score using Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS), Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) scheme, and Common Weakness Enumeration.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] CVE and other databases typically do not track vulnerabilities in software as a service products.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Submitting a CVE is voluntary for companies that discovered a vulnerability.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] The software vendor is usually not legally liable for the cost if a vulnerability is used in an attack, which creates an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:mitre-capec/vulnerability-computing] Some companies are covered by laws, such as PCI, HIPAA, and Sarbanes-Oxley, that place legal requirements on vulnerability management.
